Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.00,0:00:26.00,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,{\fs100\t(,\fs110)\frz1\fad(3000,500)\fsp0\fscx120\pos(960,800)\b0\shad0\bord0}地          球          脉          动
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.50,0:00:45.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里是地球上最后的边缘地带\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is our planet's final frontier,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.78,0:00:53.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一个只有最勇敢者 才敢涉足的地底世界\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}an inner world where only the most adventurous dare to go.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.75,0:00:50.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,{\fs60\fsp5\fad(1000,1000)\pos(960,1080)\bord0\shad3}画 外 音\N{\fs90}大卫 · 爱登堡   爵士
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.00,0:01:17.75,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,{\fs125\fsp10\fad(1000,1000)\pos(1018,1150)}洞  穴  迷  宫
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.50,0:01:51.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们脚下有着绵延不绝的洞窟和隧道\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Beneath our feet are countless miles of cave shafts and passages.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.66,0:02:09.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,墨西哥境内的燕子洞\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Cave of Swallows in Mexico,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.10,0:02:11.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,深达400多米\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}400 metres to the bottom,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.26,0:02:15.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,足以吞没整座帝国大厦\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}deep enough to engulf the Empire State Building.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.10,0:02:25.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是世界上最大的深洞\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is the biggest cave shaft in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.54,0:02:32.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而人类直到登月前两年 才第一次进入这个深渊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Yet these depths were first explored only two years before man landed on the moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.22,0:02:40.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,今天 洞穴仍是地球上 人类最少涉足的地方\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Today caves remain the least explored places on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.58,0:02:47.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是 人类绝非 这个阴暗潮湿地界的第一位到访者\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}However, human beings are seldom the first to reach these black, damp places.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.94,0:02:58.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里住着一些地球上最奇异 和最鲜为人知的动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Here, live some of the strangest and least-known animals on the planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.22,0:03:36.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这“满天星斗”其实是 几千只小动物发出的荧光\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This galaxy of little lights is created by thousands of living creatures.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.22,0:03:46.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,住在洞穴里的动物都必须 适应彻底黑暗的环境\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Any animal that lives in a cave has to cope with complete blackness,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.22,0:03:51.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是在新西兰  有些动物却能利用黑暗的条件\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but in New Zealand some have turned this darkness to their advantage.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.86,0:04:07.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一根坚韧的丝从天顶上垂下\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}A silicon strand is lowered from the ceiling,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.78,0:04:10.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,边上还有好几百根\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}alongside hundreds of others.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.62,0:04:20.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,虽然这些丝看起来很漂亮\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Beautiful though these threads are,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.06,0:04:23.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们却是阴险的陷阱\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they have a sinister purpose.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.46,0:04:27.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是一种洞穴萤火虫\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is a cave glow worm.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.98,0:04:32.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它利用一根根的丝来诱捕猎物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}To trap its prey it goes fishing with a line of silk.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.46,0:04:43.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,丝产生自萤火虫口中的腺体\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The silk comes from glands in the glow worm's mouth
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.58,0:04:46.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,上面缀着一串粘液滴\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and is loaded with droplets of mucus.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.62,0:05:05.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每条萤火虫都会吐很多根这样的丝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Each glow worm produces dozens of these threads.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.58,0:05:09.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当一排丝架设完毕后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Once its lines are set,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.46,0:05:12.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,萤火虫便用粘液将自己悬吊起来\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the glow worm hangs from a mucus hammock
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.66,0:05:16.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然后像一位耐心的钓鱼者似的 等待猎物上钩\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and waits, like a patient angler.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.30,0:05:23.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过 萤火虫并不会听天由命\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But the glow worm doesn't leave everything to chance.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.50,0:05:27.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些诡异的蓝光是一种化学反应的结果\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}That ghostly blue light is the result of a chemical reaction
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.70,0:05:31.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,由尾部的一个特殊腔囊产生\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}taking place inside a special capsule in its tail.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.86,0:05:35.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些从尾部发散出来的荧光\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The light literally shines out of its backside.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.94,0:05:39.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,正是用来吸引猎物的诱饵\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's a lure for attracting prey.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.86,0:06:10.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,昆虫总是禁不住光源的诱惑\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Insects seem irresistibly drawn towards the source
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.26,0:06:13.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,结果就被这些粘乎乎的丝拿住了\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and then get trapped by the sticky lines.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.98,0:06:24.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一旦被粘住\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Once stuck,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.42,0:06:26.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,根本没有脱逃的机会\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}there is no escape.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.50,0:06:35.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,现在 它只需收起丝线\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Now it's just a matter of reeling in the line
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.58,0:06:39.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然后慢慢吃掉尚且活着的猎物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and slowly consuming the catch - alive.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.58,0:06:57.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,通过诱捕洞穴内羽化的昆虫\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}By ensnaring the insects that hatch in this cave,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.74,0:07:03.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些萤火虫成功地解决了 终生穴居动物面临的最大难题\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}these glow worms have solved the biggest challenge that permanent cave dwellers face -
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.06,0:07:06.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,即找到长期而可靠的食物资源\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}finding a regular and reliable source of food.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.74,0:07:18.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些地底世界之所以会存在  都是因为一种岩石\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}One kind of rock makes this whole underground world possible -
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.30,0:07:19.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,石灰岩\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}limestone.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.18,0:07:22.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,世界上大部分洞穴内都存在石灰岩\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Most of the world's caves are found within it
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.02,0:07:26.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它覆盖了地球表面将近10%的面积\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and it covers nearly 10 percent of the earth's surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.66,0:07:38.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,石灰岩由海螺和 珊瑚中的矿物沉积后形成\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Limestone is composed of minerals derived from marine shells and corals,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.18,0:07:44.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以 尽管美国境内的这座石壁 如今矗立在海平面以上几百米高的地方\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so although this rocky escarpment in the United States is now hundreds of metres above sea level
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.54,0:07:47.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它实际上却是在水下形成的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}it was actually formed under water.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.50,0:07:58.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,越南下龙湾的石林\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The limestone towers of Vietnam's Ha Long Bay
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.18,0:08:01.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,能说明石灰岩与海洋的关系\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}are a reminder of this link with the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.14,0:08:05.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,起初 这整个地方都是 一整块坚固的石灰岩床\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Originally, this whole area would have been one solid block of limestone,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.62,0:08:07.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,珊瑚礁的基座\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the base of a coral reef.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.22,0:08:25.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在婆罗洲 雨水已将石灰岩 雕凿成无比尖削的石塔\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In Borneo, rain has sculptured the limestone into extremely sharp-sided pinnacles.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.30,0:08:45.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过在地下 雨水的溶解作用 还能产生其它更壮观的效果\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But the dissolving power of rainwater has other, much more dramatic effects underground.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.46,0:09:01.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,流经石灰岩的河川 到最后似乎总是无影无踪\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Rivers that flow over limestone often seem to completely disappear.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.34,0:09:18.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当水流遇到更坚硬的石灰岩床时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}When the water reaches the more resistant bed of limestone
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.78,0:09:20.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就会改变路线\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}its course is altered.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.14,0:09:26.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一旦进入地下\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Once underground,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.62,0:09:30.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水便有了一股新的、更强的侵蚀力\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the water takes on a new, more erosive power.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.18,0:09:38.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在地面上流淌时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}During its journey from the surface
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.54,0:09:41.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水从土壤中吸收了二氧化碳\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the water absorbed carbon dioxide from the soil
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.82,0:09:43.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,成为弱酸性\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}making it mildly acidic.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.10,0:09:48.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,石灰岩经过几百万年的酸蚀作用\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And over millions of years this acid eats away the limestone
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.42,0:09:51.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,形成了迷宫般的溶洞和通道\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}creating a maze of caverns and passages
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.94,0:09:54.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有的甚至深达数英里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that sometimes go on for miles.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.10,0:10:38.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是世界上最大的地下河通道\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is the biggest underground river passage in the world,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.30,0:10:42.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大到可以通过一架大型喷气式客机\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so big a jumbo jet could fly through it.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.30,0:10:45.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它就是婆罗洲的鹿洞\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's Deer Cave, in Borneo.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.38,0:10:59.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鹿洞的容量很大\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The sheer size of Deer Cave
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.50,0:11:03.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,使得大批动物到此聚集\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}allows some animals to gather there in huge numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.94,0:11:16.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里住着数量惊人的300万只犬吻蝠\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}A staggering 3 million wrinkle-lipped bats live here.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.34,0:11:22.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些蝙蝠倒挂在洞壁和天顶上\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The bats roost high on the walls and ceilings
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.18,0:11:24.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们在此完全不受外界因素的干扰\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}where they're well protected from the outside elements
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.70,0:11:26.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,还能躲开天敌\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and safe from predators.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.82,0:11:36.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们高悬在洞穴上方时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And while they're up here
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.50,0:11:39.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,会产生一种非常重要的东西\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the bats produce something very important.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.46,0:11:49.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这堆100多米高的东西 全都是蝙蝠的排泄物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This hundred metre high mound is made entirely of bat droppings -
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.74,0:11:51.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,粪便\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}guano.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.78,0:12:18.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地面上爬满了密密麻麻的蟑螂\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Its surface is covered by a thick carpet of cockroaches,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.54,0:12:20.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们的数量无以为计\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}hundreds of thousands of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.26,0:12:32.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洞穴是地球上少数几种 不直接依赖阳光的生态环境之一\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Caves are one of the few habitats on Earth not directly powered by sunlight.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.30,0:12:40.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在缺少植物的情况下 这里的食物链 完全依赖供应不断的蝙蝠粪便\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In the absence of plants this food chain is based on a continuous supply of bat droppings.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.42,0:12:55.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,蟑螂的食物就是粪便\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The cockroaches feed on the guano
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.62,0:12:58.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以及任何掉进里面的东西\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and anything that falls into it.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.66,0:13:28.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,粪便也能养活其它种类的蟑螂\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The droppings also support other types of cockroaches
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.30,0:13:32.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们一天大部分时间都呆在洞壁上\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}which spend part of their day resting on cave walls.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.18,0:13:40.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些蟑螂也接连成为了 洞穴大蚰蜒的美餐\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These in turn become food for giant cave centipedes,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.82,0:13:43.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有的蚰蜒能长到20厘米长\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}some more than 20 centimetres long.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.34,0:13:49.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,奇怪的是 这里甚至还有螃蟹\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Bizarrely, there are crabs here, too,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.90,0:13:53.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们从粪便中过滤营养物质\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}sifting through the droppings for nutrients.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.78,0:14:03.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所有这些动物都在洞穴内度过一生\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}All these animals spend their entire lives within the cave.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.90,0:14:09.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们完全依赖的食物消化残渣 都是来自于外界\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They're totally dependant on the digested remains of food that's brought here from outside.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.46,0:14:39.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每天傍晚 只是前后2小时内\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Each evening in just two hours
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.02,0:14:42.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,300万只蝙蝠一起离开安全的洞穴\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}three million bats leave the safety of the cave
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.58,0:14:45.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在森林外围捕食昆虫\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}to hunt for insects in the forest outside.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.42,0:14:51.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但并非所有的蝙蝠都能返回\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But not all will return.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.10,0:15:13.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,蝙蝠离开山洞后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}As they leave the cave
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.54,0:15:17.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,即在空中组成一个面包圈一样的队列\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the stream of bats form a doughnut-shaped ring.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.82,0:15:25.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,旋绕的蝙蝠群似乎已将 棕腹隼雕弄得晕头转向\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The wheeling bats seem to confuse a rufus-bellied eagle,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.26,0:15:30.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但它们仍须躲过 其它更专业的猛禽的攻击\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but they must still survive the attacks of other, more specialised, birds of prey.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.46,0:15:47.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,游隼和蝠鹞是鸟类中的喷气式战斗机\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Peregrine falcons and bat hawks are the jetfighters of the bird world.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.74,0:16:20.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,天黑后 再高超的捕猎本领 也将无用武之地\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Good hunting will end as the light fades
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.58,0:16:24.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,于是蝠鹞一边飞一边吞下猎物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so the bat hawks bolt their catches on the wing
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.54,0:16:27.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然后径直返回继续捕猎\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and fly straight back for more.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.26,0:16:32.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,任何一只脱离群体的蝙蝠\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Any bat separated from the group
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.46,0:16:36.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,立刻成为显眼的目标 很快便遭了殃\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}becomes a clear and obvious target and is asking for trouble.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.82,0:16:51.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而 每天傍晚的攻击只会 对蝙蝠数量产生很小的影响\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Yet the nightly onslaught has little impact on bat numbers -
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.98,0:16:57.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,到了早上 大多数蝙蝠 仍会安然无恙地回到洞中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}by the morning the vast majority will be back in the safety of the cave.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.94,0:17:11.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,蝙蝠并非婆罗洲洞窟中的唯一常客\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Bats are not the only commuters in these Bornean caves.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:11.38,0:17:13.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里也有“做日班”的居民\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There's a day shift as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.50,0:17:21.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,完成白天的狩猎工作后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Returning from hunting in the sunlight
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.70,0:17:28.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些住客利用它们响亮的叫声 在漆黑一片的洞穴通道内辨别方向\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}these commuters rely on their loud clicks to find their way through the cave passages in total darkness.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.62,0:17:36.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们就是洞金丝燕\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They're cave swiftlets.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.18,0:17:41.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,和蝙蝠一样  它们也利用回声定位来导航\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Like bats they use echolocation to navigate.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.06,0:17:43.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们必须有光才能看清前方的路\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}We need lights to see what's going on,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.62,0:17:49.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是金丝燕却能在黑暗中 准确无误地到达自己的筑巢点\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but in the pitch black the swiftlets manage unerringly to locate their individual nesting sites,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.50,0:17:52.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而它们的巢窝相隔不过几厘米远\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}which are only a few centimetres across.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.98,0:18:02.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们至今仍未能完全了解 这种了不起的本领\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's a remarkable skill and one we still do not fully understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.22,0:18:09.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些鸟之所以特别还有另外一个原因\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These birds are unusual for another reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.22,0:18:14.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们小巧的杯状燕窝完全由唾液丝筑建\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Their little cup-like nests are made entirely from threads of saliva.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.74,0:18:23.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每个燕窝得花上30多天才能完工\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It takes more than 30 days to complete one.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.42,0:18:27.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,燕窝是非常珍贵的东西\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The nests are very precious objects,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.10,0:18:30.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不仅只是针对这些鸟而言\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and not only for the birds.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.98,0:18:52.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,500年来 人们一直采集洞金丝燕的燕窝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}For 500 years people have been harvesting the nests of cave swiftlets.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.38,0:19:07.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是一项非常危险的工作\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's a very risky business.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.94,0:19:10.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,事实上没有任何安全措施\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}with virtually no safety equipment
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.14,0:19:16.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,采集者利用树藤编成的梯子爬到洞穴的最高处\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and using ladders made from forest vines the gatherers climb into the highest reaches of the cave
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.66,0:19:19.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,通常高出地面60多米\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}often more than 60 metres from the floor.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:28.42,0:19:31.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这项工作看起来极度危险\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The work may be hazardous in the extreme,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.14,0:19:33.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但却能得到丰厚的回报\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but the rewards are great.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.10,0:19:45.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洞金丝燕的纯白燕窝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The pure white nests of cave swiftlets
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.74,0:19:49.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是燕窝羹的主要成分\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}are the main ingredient of birds' nest soup
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.22,0:19:53.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每克燕窝的价值堪比白银\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and gram for gram are worth as much as silver.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:55.06,0:19:59.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,燕窝被摘去后  金丝燕很快又会再吐一个\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}As soon as its nest is removed a bird will immediately build another.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.94,0:20:03.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以 只要这种利润可观的 采摘行为得到适当控制\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}So, as long as this valuable harvest is properly controlled,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.02,0:20:06.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,燕群仍旧可以长盛不衰\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the colonies will continue to flourish.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.98,0:20:22.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,婆罗洲的这些洞窟是世界上最大的洞穴\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These Bornean caves are among the biggest in the world
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.26,0:20:23.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们仍在不断扩大\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and they're still getting bigger
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.74,0:20:29.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,因为每年雨水都会侵蚀掉少许石灰岩\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}as each year rainwater eats away a little more limestone.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.10,0:20:42.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可是洞里的水不光只是侵蚀\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But water in caves doesn't only erode.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.74,0:20:45.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们还能造景\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It also builds.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.54,0:20:55.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些水中含有溶解的碳酸钙\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This water is loaded with dissolved limestone
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.30,0:20:57.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当它与洞内空气接触时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and when it meets the air in the cave
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.58,0:21:00.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其中的一些就会沉淀为一种矿物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}some of that is deposited as a mineral -
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.82,0:21:02.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,方解石\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}calcite.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.38,0:21:05.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,随着它的积累\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}As it builds up
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.62,0:21:09.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,方解石形成了悬在洞顶上的装饰物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so the calcite forms decorations that hang from the ceiling -
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.78,0:21:11.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,钟乳石\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}stalactites.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.90,0:21:23.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每滴水珠只会留下极少量的方解石微粒\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Each drop leaves behind only a miniscule amount of calcite,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.22,0:21:27.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但随着时间的推移  它们变成了最引人入胜的景观\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but over time the process can produce some spectacular results.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.86,0:22:00.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,若是水从洞顶滴落的速度较快\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}If the water seeps though the ceiling quickly,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.62,0:22:04.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,方解石就会在洞穴地面上沉积\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}then the calcite is deposited on the floor of the cave
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.06,0:22:07.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最后形成石笋\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and that creates stalagmites.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.14,0:22:19.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水流和气流的变化\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Variations in water flow and the air currents
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.38,0:22:25.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,造就了千姿百态的溶洞地形  但它们的形成过程都是一样的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}produce an infinite variety of forms, but all are created by the same process -
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.50,0:22:29.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,都是由水溶碳酸钙缓慢沉淀而来\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the slow deposition of dissolved limestone.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.70,0:22:35.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,钟乳石与石笋相遇后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And when stalactite meets stalagmite
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.70,0:22:38.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,便形成了石柱\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}a column is born.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.14,0:23:04.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,北美洲卡尔斯巴德溶洞中的这些构造\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Structures like these in North America's Carlsbad Cavern
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.98,0:23:08.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,经历了数千年的形成过程\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}can take many thousands of years to develop.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.30,0:23:13.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但有时洞穴内的这些活动会完全停止\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But sometimes the formations in a cave stop growing altogether.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.66,0:23:47.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,墨西哥的这些水洞 几千年来几乎保持不变\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These flooded caves in Mexico have remained virtually unchanged for thousands of years.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.62,0:23:52.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,自从上一个冰川期以来  它们便已和外界隔绝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Since the last Ice Age they've become cut off from the outside world.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.30,0:23:56.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而它们对地面上的生物 却有着极其深远的影响\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Yet their impact on life on the surface has been huge.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.22,0:24:07.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,500年前 它们维系着 一个世界上最伟大的文明\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}500 years ago they supported one of the world's great civilisations
Dialogue: 0,0:24:07.98,0:24:09.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,玛雅\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the Maya.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.26,0:24:19.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,墨西哥的尤卡坦半岛 没有河流、湖泊和小溪\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula has no rivers, lakes or streams
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.66,0:24:26.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,因此玛雅文化完全依赖于沼穴 ——地下水洞的入口\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so the Maya relied on the cenotes - the flooded entrances to the water-filled caves.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.26,0:24:35.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些水潭是整个地区 唯一的露天淡水资源\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These flooded shafts are the region's only source of open fresh water.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.34,0:24:42.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,沼穴于是成了巨大的淡水井\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The cenotes are, in effect, gigantic fresh water wells.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.90,0:25:10.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里远离给予生命的阳光\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Away from the life-giving rays of sunshine
Dialogue: 0,0:25:10.10,0:25:13.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,似乎不太可能会有植物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}one might not expect to find plants.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.78,0:25:24.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是在黑暗的洞穴通道内\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But in the darkness of the cave tunnels
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.34,0:25:29.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大型热带树木的根系 却已穿透石灰岩裂缝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}roots of giant tropical trees have pushed their way through cracks in the limestone
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.62,0:25:32.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,伸入到水洞之中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}to reach the flooded caverns.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.58,0:25:34.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果没有这些水\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Without this water
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.98,0:25:39.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,尤卡坦半岛的森林不可能长得如此茂盛\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the Yucatan's forest could not grow so luxuriantly.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.50,0:26:02.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,玛雅人固然知道 它们的生活离不开这些水\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Maya knew that their lives depended on this water,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:02.38,0:26:05.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但只有借助现代科技\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but it's only with the help of today's technology
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.30,0:26:12.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们才能完全了解 这些地下水道的重要性及其规模\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that we've come to appreciate the full significance and scale of these flooded passageways.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:15.50,0:26:22.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,人们迄今为止已绘制了350英里的 尤卡坦半岛地下水系图\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}So far, more than 350 miles of underwater galleries in the Yucatan have been mapped,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.62,0:26:29.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但仍旧无人知晓 这个地下水世界究竟有多大\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but still nobody yet knows the true extend of this subterranean waterworld.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.34,0:26:31.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以及它形成的原因\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And with good reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.82,0:26:37.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地下水洞是出了名的危险\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Underwater caving is notoriously dangerous.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:38.06,0:26:41.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最近的出口可能远在 几百米之外或者更远的地方\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}When the nearest exit may be hundreds of metres or more away,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.78,0:26:45.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在这里 耗尽氧气将是致命的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}running out of air down here would be fatal.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:48.74,0:26:50.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,为了避免迷路\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}To avoid getting lost
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.34,0:26:53.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,潜水员必须随身携带一捆轴线\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}divers carry with them a spool of string.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.10,0:26:54.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这成了它们的救生索\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It becomes their lifeline -
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.06,0:26:56.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,绝对如此\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}literally.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.58,0:27:12.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这根线同时也是测量尺\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The string also doubles as a measuring tape -
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.78,0:27:19.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在墨西哥的这个地方 这种科技被用来 测绘世界上最大的地下水洞\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}a technique that has been used here, in Mexico, to chart the largest underwater cave in the world -
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.14,0:27:21.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,全长达100多英里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}all 100 miles of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.74,0:27:35.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洞穴探险需要不时挤过 一些狭窄的岩石缝隙\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Cave exploration often requires you to push yourself through narrow gaps in the rock.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.78,0:27:39.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洞穴专家称之为“瓶颈”\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Cavers call such places 'squeezes.'
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.22,0:27:49.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,“瓶颈”越是狭窄\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The tighter the squeeze,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.82,0:27:54.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,便越有可能损坏一些重要的生存设备\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the greater the chance of damaging some vital life-support system.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.14,0:28:25.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在这种情况下  潜水员很容易迷失方向\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In these conditions a diver could easily become disorientated
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.18,0:28:27.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而这将导致送命\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and that could be fatal.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:40.82,0:28:45.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地下水洞还会以别的方式戏弄你\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The flooded caverns can play tricks on you in other ways.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.50,0:28:55.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这看上去像是空气\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}What seems like air,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.18,0:28:55.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不对\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}isn't.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.10,0:29:00.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它只是另一种水\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's just another kind of water.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.38,0:29:09.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里是盐跃层\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is a halocline -
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.54,0:29:12.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,淡水与咸水的交汇处\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}a meeting of fresh and salt water.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:15.34,0:29:21.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,咸水来自海洋 比重较重  来自丛林的淡水在其上方流动\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Fresh water from the jungle flows over the heavier salt water from the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.22,0:29:25.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,咸水层的含氧量很低\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The saltwater layer is extremely low in oxygen
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.54,0:29:29.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对动物而言是极为困难的生境\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}making it a particularly difficult place for animals to live.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.86,0:29:31.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但有些动物却能在此生存\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Yet some have managed it,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.94,0:29:37.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,例如桨足虫——一种最古老的甲壳动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}like the remiped, one of the most ancient of all living crustaceans.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.22,0:29:49.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,玛雅人知道沼穴的重要性\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Maya understood the importance of the cenotes,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.10,0:29:56.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但他们从不知道这些水下通道 其实是地下河的入口\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but they could never have known that these flooded passageways were actually the beginning of subterranean rivers,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:56.46,0:29:59.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们最终都流向大海\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}all of which eventually flow out to the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.30,0:30:13.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,咸水与淡水不同 不会溶解石灰岩\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Salt water, unlike fresh water, does not erode limestone,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:13.74,0:30:19.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以大部分海洋洞窟 是在海浪的机械冲击下形成的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so most sea caves are created by the mechanical pounding of the waves.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.78,0:30:31.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,新西兰坡·骑士岛的 岩礁下布满了海蚀洞\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The rocky outcrops of New Zealand's Poor Knight Islands are riddled with sea caves
Dialogue: 0,0:30:31.66,0:30:33.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,与婆罗洲的洞窟一样\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and just like those in Borneo
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.58,0:30:37.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们也成了许多动物的重要庇护所\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they have become important shelters for many species.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.66,0:30:44.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,经过一天开放水域的觅食之后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}After a day feeding in the open water
Dialogue: 0,0:30:44.34,0:30:48.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大群雀鲷返回到洞窟中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}vast shoals of demoiselle fish return to the caves,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.46,0:30:51.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里是它们躲避天敌的地方\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}which they use as a refuge from predators.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:54.10,0:30:57.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对于这些鱼来说  洞穴是理想的过夜场所\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}For these fish the caves are a night time retreat,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:57.94,0:31:00.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但它们并非这里的唯一住客\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but they're not the only commuters in here.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.86,0:31:04.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里还有其它 按照不同日程表生活的鱼\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There are other fish working to a different schedule.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.58,0:31:14.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大眼鲷相当于蝙蝠\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The bigeyes are the equivalent of bats.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.98,0:31:18.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们每天晚上出洞觅食\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Night feeders leave the cave each evening.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.30,0:31:24.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,和所有洞穴动物一样\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And like all cave commuters
Dialogue: 0,0:31:24.86,0:31:28.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们在出发阶段最容易遭受攻击\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they are most vulnerable at the scheduled time of departure.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:39.82,0:31:45.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当大群蝙蝠密集地通过瓶颈出口时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}A bottleneck funnels these exiting bats into dense concentrations
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.78,0:31:48.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,很容易引起其它动物的注意\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}attracting the attention of others.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:14.90,0:32:19.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,蝙蝠能利用回声定位觉察到蛇\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The bats can detect the snakes using echolocation,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.34,0:32:21.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而蛇则完全处于黑暗之中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but the snakes are literally in the dark -
Dialogue: 0,0:32:21.90,0:32:23.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们看不见任何东西\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they can see nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:36.86,0:32:40.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这种攻击更像是在碰运气\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The strikes seem to be largely hit-and-miss,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:42.38,0:32:45.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过蛇也有自己的秘密武器\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but the snakes have a secret weapon.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.74,0:32:49.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们实际上能感觉到 每一只飞过的蝙蝠\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They can actually sense each bat flying past.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.34,0:32:54.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,位于头部的“热眼”能觉察到 飞行中的蝙蝠散发出的热量\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Receptors in the snake's head pick up the heat given off by the flying bats,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:54.94,0:32:57.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,正如这幅热影像所示\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}as this thermal image shows.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.82,0:33:07.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每一只蝙蝠在蛇“眼”前都是活灵活现\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}To the snakes the bats are apparently glowing
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.46,0:33:10.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这也给了它们瞄准目标的机会\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and this gives them something to aim at.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:31.82,0:33:35.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是洞栖动物必须付出的代价\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is the price that these cave commuters must pay
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.86,0:33:39.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以换取它们白天在陆地上的庇护\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}for their daytime sanctuary on the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:39.14,0:33:44.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,难怪其它洞穴生物 要终生居住在洞穴中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Small wonder then that there are other cave dwellers that stay put.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.58,0:33:53.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,很多洞穴都和岛屿一样\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Many caves are like islands -
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.02,0:33:58.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,与外界及其它洞穴隔绝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}cut off from the outside world and from other caves.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.94,0:34:12.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这种孤立环境导致进化产生 各种各样奇怪的生物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This isolation has resulted in the evolution of some various strange creatures.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:14.42,0:34:17.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们都是洞穴专家\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They are the cave specialists -
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.18,0:34:23.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,穴居动物——从不出洞并且 永远不见天日的动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}troglodytes, animals that never emerge from the caves or see daylight.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:35.38,0:34:37.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,泰国的这些穴居动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These troglodytes from Thailand
Dialogue: 0,0:34:38.02,0:34:41.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可能是地球上最奇特的动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}are possibly the most specialised creatures on Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:34:41.78,0:34:45.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,因为它们只生活在洞穴瀑布中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}for they live only in cave waterfalls.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:46.06,0:34:49.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,世界上所有的洞穴天使鱼\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The entire population of these cave angel fish
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.46,0:34:53.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可能只存在于两个较小的洞穴中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}seems to be restricted to just two small caves.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.46,0:35:00.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其它穴居动物也是同样的情况\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's the same story with other troglodytes.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:00.02,0:35:05.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,世界上可能只有不到100只 野生洞栖童态河溪螈\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There may well be less than a hundred Texas cave salamanders in the wild.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:21.38,0:35:28.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而伯利兹白蟹是另一个 洞穴生态系统中的特有物种\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And the Belizean white crab is another creature that is unique to just one cave system.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:33.50,0:35:35.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,由于一直生活在黑暗之中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Living in perpetual darkness
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.66,0:35:38.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们不仅失去了皮肤色素\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they have all not only lost the pigment in their skin,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.82,0:35:40.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,眼睛也退化了\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but also their eyes.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.70,0:35:46.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,眼睛的退化需要经历数千代的演变\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It takes thousands of generations for eyes to be lost,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:46.46,0:35:51.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以这些物种必定 与世隔绝了相当长的一段时间\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so these species must have been isolated for a very long time.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.06,0:36:01.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过这些瞎眼的蝾螈 进化出了其它发达的感觉器官\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But the blind salamander has other highly developed sensory organs.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:03.90,0:36:10.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,皮肤上的探测器能觉察到 猎物引起的最微小的水流变化\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Receptors in their skin detect minute movements in the water made by its prey.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.06,0:36:21.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,外生的鳃帮助它们 在极度缺氧的水中呼吸\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}External gills help it to breathe in water that is particularly low in oxygen.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:33.10,0:36:37.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洞穴天使鱼以急流中的细菌为食\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The cave angel fish feed on bacteria in the fast flowing water
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.06,0:36:42.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们用鳍上的小钩紧紧抓住岩壁\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}keeping their grip with microscopic hooks on their fins.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:52.58,0:36:55.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,食物总是很紧缺\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Food is often in short supply
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.18,0:36:57.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,像螃蟹这样的穴居动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and troglodytes like the crab
Dialogue: 0,0:36:57.42,0:37:01.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,必须得吃任何从外边冲进洞内的东西\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}have to survive on whatever washes into the cave from outside.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.82,0:37:09.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,童态河溪螈可能 已有几个月没有吃东西了\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The salamander might not encounter food for several months,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:09.54,0:37:11.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以只要眼前有食物出现\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}so when something does come along
Dialogue: 0,0:37:11.58,0:37:13.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它绝对不会放过\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}it can't afford to miss it.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:20.26,0:37:26.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些奇异的洞栖生物能如此成功地生存 的确令人称奇\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's astonishing that these extraordinary cave dwellers manage to survive at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:26.86,0:37:29.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可是有一个洞穴的环境过于险恶\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But one cave is so inhospitable
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.42,0:37:33.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不管什么生物似乎都不可能在那里生存\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that one would not expect it to contain any life whatsoever.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:38.94,0:37:42.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,从墨西哥露兹别墅山洞流出来的水\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The water flowing out of the Villa Luz cave in Mexico
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.02,0:37:46.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,竟然被硫酸染成了白色\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}is actually coloured white with sulphuric acid.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.30,0:38:04.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,探险家们进入这个危险的山洞时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Explorers entering this dangerous cave
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.22,0:38:07.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,必须戴上防毒面具 并携带通话器\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}must wear respirators and carry monitors.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:07.94,0:38:11.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有毒气体很快就会达到致命的程度\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Poisonous gases rise to fatal levels so quickly
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.38,0:38:14.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以即时预警设备是最重要的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that an early warning system is essential.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:18.94,0:38:22.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,蝙蝠之所以能生存是因为 它们始终呆在天窗附近\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Bats survive by staying close to the skylights,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:22.70,0:38:27.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是深入洞穴必然极度危险\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but venturing deep into the cave is very dangerous indeed.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:36.42,0:38:42.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些毒气的源头位于地下几英里处\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The source of these toxic fumes lies several miles below.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.14,0:38:47.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,硫化氢气体从地壳内的油气储层中溢出\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Hydrogen sulphide gas bubbles up from oil deposits in the earth's crust.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:47.38,0:38:49.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,与水中的氧发生化合反应\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It mixes with oxygen and the water,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.82,0:38:52.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,产生了硫酸\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and forms sulphuric acid.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:03.30,0:39:07.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鱼类似乎不太可能生活在这种环境中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These are not the sort of conditions in which you would expect to find fish,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:07.62,0:39:10.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而这些洞栖帆鳍? 看上去却是悠然自得\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}yet these cave mollies seem to thrive
Dialogue: 0,0:39:10.66,0:39:14.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,尽管这里是酸性低含氧量环境\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}despite the acid and the low levels of oxygen.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:16.50,0:39:20.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,事实上 这里的生物数量 远比人们预料的更多\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There is, in fact, more life here than anyone would think possible,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.54,0:39:25.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过更大的惊奇莫过于 那些更奇怪的东西\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but the biggest surprise is something altogether more bizarre.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:35.42,0:39:43.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些奇特的钟乳石状的结构  确切地说 叫做“鼻涕石”\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These strange stalactite-like formations are known, rather appropriately, as snotites,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:43.78,0:39:48.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其末端滴落的液滴就是硫酸\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the drops dripping from the ends are sulphuric acid,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:48.14,0:39:50.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,酸性强到足以腐蚀皮肤\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}strong enough to burn skin.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:53.98,0:39:58.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,“鼻涕石”其实是大型菌落\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The snotites are, in fact, vast colonies of bacteria,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.18,0:40:01.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每天能长长1厘米\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}capable of going a centimetre a day.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:05.74,0:40:07.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在这个没有阳光的世界里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In this world without sunlight
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.70,0:40:13.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些细菌只能从硫化氢气体中吸收能量\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}these bacteria extract energy from the hydrogen sulphide gas.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:17.26,0:40:21.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,像这样的细菌被称为嗜极生物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Bacteria like these are known as extremofile
Dialogue: 0,0:40:21.26,0:40:25.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,因为它们能在这种极端环境中生存\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}because of their ability to survive in such extreme conditions.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:28.14,0:40:33.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些嗜极生物还在这个洞中 扮演着另一个非常重要的角色\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And these extremofiles play another important role in this cave.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:33.06,0:40:36.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,令人吃惊的是  它们竟然是食物链中的第一环\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Surprisingly, they are the basis of a food chain
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.62,0:40:41.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,用以养活其它生物  例如这些蚋的幼虫\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}which supports, amongst other creatures, the larvae of these midges.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:50.62,0:40:54.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,露兹别墅山洞的生态系统的确非同寻常\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Villa Luz's ecosystem was certainly very remarkable,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:54.42,0:40:59.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是洞穴探险家们 很快又有了更惊人的发现\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but cave explorers were soon to make an even more astonishing discovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:11.86,0:41:17.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,谁能想到在这些贫瘠的土地下 有一处地下仙境\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Beneath this arid landscape lies a subterranean wonderland.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:22.90,0:41:26.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,没有水的地方似乎不可能有洞穴\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Without water one might not expect to find any caves,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:26.50,0:41:30.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是在美国这些荒凉起伏的山崖之下\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but beneath these rolling desert slopes in the United States
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.82,0:41:37.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,存在着一座世界上最长、最深  也最令人惊奇的洞穴\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}lies one of the longest, deepest and most surprising caves in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:41.30,0:41:45.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它的秘密直到1986年才被人们发现\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Its secrets remained unknown until 1986,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:45.50,0:41:48.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洞穴专家们在松散的岩层中 挖出了一条几十米深的通道\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}when cavers dug through several metres of loose rock
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.98,0:41:51.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,直达这个深渊的底部\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}to the bottom of this pit.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.30,0:41:57.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他们把这个洞命名为“龙舌兰洞”\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They named the cave 'Lechuguilla'
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.34,0:42:04.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,自从那次发现之后  迄今已测绘了120多英里的地道\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and since this discovery more than 120 miles of passageways have been mapped.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:09.22,0:42:11.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,第一批探险家进入这个洞后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}When the first explorers descended,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:11.42,0:42:14.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,没有一个人能预料到它竟然有这么大\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}no-one guessed at the sheer size of this cave.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.94,0:42:18.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,即便如此 这也不能算是最大的惊奇\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But even that was not going to be the biggest surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:18.94,0:42:23.00,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不久他们便意识到龙舌兰洞很快就会\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Little did they realise that Lechuguilla would soon
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.00,0:42:28.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,被全世界的洞穴专家公认为地球上最美丽的洞穴\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}be regarded by cavers the world over as the most beautiful of all caves.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:28.10,0:42:34.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,因为他们发现了一些 地底世界中最精美的构造\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They were about to discover some of the most exquisite formations ever seen underground.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:48.34,0:42:53.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,石壁上布满了光洁美丽的脆弱结晶\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The walls were covered with the most delicate and fragile crystals.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:08.34,0:43:11.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,许多结晶都是由石膏组成\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Many of these crystals were made of gypsum,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:11.58,0:43:14.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一种硫酸钙沉积而来的矿物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}a mineral that comes from limestone.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:14.38,0:43:17.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们绵延不绝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And there was mile after mile of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:34.26,0:43:37.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水是大部分洞穴的建造者\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Water is the creator of most caves,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:37.62,0:43:40.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是 和其它石灰岩溶洞不同的是\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but, unlike all other limestone caves,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:40.30,0:43:45.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,龙舌兰洞中的岩石并非被流水侵蚀\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Lechuguilla's rock had not been eaten away by running rainwater.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:46.86,0:43:49.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而是因为其它的作用力\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Something else was responsible.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:57.30,0:44:03.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,龙舌兰洞中唯一的水 来自这些平静清澈的水塘\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The only water Lechuguilla has are these wonderfully still clear pools.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:08.58,0:44:11.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,随着探险家们深入洞穴\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}As the explorers went deeper into the cave,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:11.30,0:44:16.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他们发现了成片叹为观止的地貌\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they came across whole galleries filled with the most unusual formations,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:16.14,0:44:21.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,例如这些5米高的石锥  上面布满了雪霜一样的松脆结晶\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}like these 5-metre cones, frosted with the most delicate crystals.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:50.10,0:44:52.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,龙舌兰洞的石膏结晶群\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It was Lechuguilla's gypsum crystals
Dialogue: 0,0:44:52.94,0:44:57.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,使科学家们产生了 这个巨洞如何形成的疑问\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that made scientists question how these caverns were formed.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:59.34,0:45:06.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他们发现龙舌兰洞的石灰岩 实际上是被硫酸侵蚀的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They discovered that Lechuguilla's limestone had actually been eaten away by sulphuric acid,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:06.34,0:45:09.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,凿穿了差不多数英里的石灰岩\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}cutting through literally miles of limestone.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:26.82,0:45:30.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,硫酸在溶解石灰岩的同时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And when sulphuric acid dissolves limestone
Dialogue: 0,0:45:30.06,0:45:32.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,也留下了石膏\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}it leaves behind gypsum,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:32.14,0:45:35.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们最终形成了龙舌兰洞的奇景\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the basis of Lechuguilla's remarkable formations.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:36.02,0:45:37.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里有一组景观\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And there was one set,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:37.58,0:45:39.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,位于地表之下1英里多的地方\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}more than a mile from the surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:39.90,0:45:42.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,美得简直无法令人相信\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that almost defied belief.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:58.78,0:46:03.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,“灯饰大厅”是最后被发现的厅洞\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Chandelier Ballroom was the ultimate discovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:03.18,0:46:05.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里尽是6米多长的结晶群\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}With its six-metre long crystals
Dialogue: 0,0:46:05.54,0:46:10.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它可以说是世界上最奇异的厅洞\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}it's surely the most bizarre cave chamber in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:50.90,0:46:55.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而石壁上还有更惊人的发现\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And the walls had one further surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.18,0:47:03.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,嗜极细菌在岩壁上自我生长\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Extremofile bacteria were found to be feeding on the rock itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.86,0:47:14.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,生命彻底脱离太阳能量 却依然生存的现象\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The discovery of life that exists without drawing any of its energy from the sun
Dialogue: 0,0:47:14.34,0:47:20.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,再一次向我们展示了地底世界 是多么的复杂和惊人\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}shows us once again how complex and surprising the underground world can be.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:24.46,0:47:30.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每年 探险家们都会测绘 上百英里新的洞穴通道\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Each year explorers chart over a hundred miles of new cave passages.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:32.10,0:47:35.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但世界上仍有一半石灰岩洞尚未被开发\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But with half the world's limestone still to be explored,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:36.10,0:47:42.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,谁知道还会有多少个龙舌兰洞 等着人们去发现呢\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}who knows how many Lechuguillas are still waiting to be discovered?

